A Time Series Analysis of Different Economy Related Metrics in Turkey

Introduction

Although a standard criteria for evaluating a countryâ€™s level of economic development is mostly considered as income per capita, GDP per capita, there are many other evaluation metrics that can be considered, such as unemployment rate. Though unemployment is a general problem for the whole world, the degree of unemployment in Turkey has been especially high in respect to the other countries in the region at the same economic level. According to the graph on the web page statista.com an upward trend in unemployment rate is obvious since 2012. So as to examine the effects of employment in Turkey on other economy related metrics, the dataset of total number of employed people in a month is used in this analysis.

Employment is aside, production comes to the mind, as for another economy related topic. Although there has been many obsolete techniques used in agriculture, the agriculture production in Turkey has always been a strong and developing industry for the country. Thanks to the fertile and arable lands and favourable climate, different fruits and vegetables grow in different regions of Turkey, and most of the population in the rural areas earn their income from agriculture. To analyze the production, an important metric industrial production index is used in this study. According to the investopedia.com the industrial production index (IPI) is defined as a monthly economic indicator measuring real output in the manufacturing, mining, electric, and gas industries, relative to a base year. Therefore, IPI is an important macroeconomic indicator especially for economists and investors.

Another important metric that is used in this analysis is total number of exported goods. Exports are incredibly important to modern economies because they offer people and firms many more markets for their goods. One of the core functions of diplomacy and foreign policy between governments is to foster economic trade, encouraging exports and imports for the benefit of all trading parties.

As the metrics, the number of employed people, exported goods and IPI explained above; data manipulations, correlation and visual analysis will be conducted in this study. The time series data is provided by Elektronik Veri DaÄŸÄ±tÄ±m Sistemi. Because of the availability of data, monthly data from 2013 up to 2020, which is not included, is used. Main goal of this study is to answer if there are any correlations between these metrics and also to see any time series related property in the dataset.

Manipulations

Initially, the xlsx file contains some extra parts: â€˜Notlarâ€™ and â€˜Seri AÃ§Ä±klamalarÄ±â€™. They create confusion after the data is read as if they are some sort of data points. What is more, date was in the form of (month, year). So some manipulations were necessary to handle these problems and filter the time range. Because date column is converted to better handled date format, date value appears as the first day of the month which actually indicates that month.

colname_filterdate <- function(someDT,old_colname,new_colname){
  
  setnames(someDT, 'Tarih', 'date')
  someDT <- someDT %>% filter(grepl('-', date))
  
  setnames(someDT, old_colname, new_colname)
  someDT[,date := as.Date(as.yearmon(date))]
  someDT <- someDT[date >=  ymd(20130101) & date <  ymd(20200101) ]
  
  someDT$month <- format( someDT$date, "%m")
  someDT$year <- format( someDT$date,"%Y")
  someDT$day <- as.numeric( format(someDT$date, "%d"))
  
  # because there is no forecasting in this study, no further time tag extraction is applied
  
  someDT[,data:=as.numeric(data)]
  return(someDT)
}


number_of_employed <- colname_filterdate(number_of_employed, 'TP TIG03', 'data')
number_of_exported <- colname_filterdate(number_of_exported, 'TP IHRISICREV4 TT', 'data')
industrial_production_index <- colname_filterdate(industrial_production_index, 'TP SANAYREV4 Y1', 'data')

Visualizations

When we plot graphs, we can see a clear annual seasonal pattern in every graph in addition to an increasing trend. It is highly likely that all of these metrics show an seasonal pattern.

ggplot(number_of_employed, aes(x=date, y=data)) + geom_line()+

This high seasonality in these metrics can be also derived from the autocorrelation in time series data. If we plot the autocorrelation functions, there must high values at lag 12, indicating this seasonality.

total_dataset <- cbind(employed = number_of_employed$data, 
                            ipi = industrial_production_index$data,
                            exported = number_of_exported$data)

ggcorrplot(cor(total_dataset), hc.order = TRUE,
           lab = TRUE)

It seems like there is a relatively high correlation between the number of employed people and ipi in the dataset.

print(cor.test(total_dataset[,'employed'], total_dataset[,'ipi']))
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  total_dataset[, "employed"] and total_dataset[, "ipi"]
## t = 10.01, df = 82, p-value = 7.129e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6268577 0.8248389
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.7415871

This super small p value shows we can reject the null hypothesis stating the correlation between these metrics is equal to 0.

total_dataset <- data.table(employed = number_of_employed$data, 
                            ipi = industrial_production_index$data,
                            exported = number_of_exported$data,
                            date = number_of_exported$date)

cor_emp_ipi <- total_dataset[,.(cor_emp_ipi = cor(employed, ipi)),by=year(date)]
cor_emp_exp <- total_dataset[,.(cor_emp_exp = cor(employed, exported)),by=year(date)]
cor_exp_ipi <- total_dataset[,.(cor_exp_ipi = cor(exported, ipi)),by=year(date)]

ggplot(cor_emp_ipi, aes(x=year, y=cor_emp_ipi)) + 
  geom_point(aes(size=cor_emp_ipi)) +
  labs(title = "Annual Correlations Between Number of Employed and IPI", 
       x = "Year",
       y = "Correlation")

These correlations do not show any significant relationship between the number of employed and IPI, though there is a relatively high correlation in 2017.

ggplot(cor_emp_exp, aes(x=year, y=cor_emp_exp)) + 
  geom_point(aes(size=cor_emp_exp)) +
  labs(title = "Annual Correlations Between Number of Employed and Exported Goods", 
       x = "Year",
       y = "Correlation")

Although there is a relatively high positive correlation in 2017 and negative correlation in 2015, yearly correlations are found around zero between the number of employed people and exported goods. We can claim there is no significant relationship between these metrics.

ggplot(cor_exp_ipi, aes(x=year, y=cor_exp_ipi)) + 
  geom_point(aes(size=cor_exp_ipi)) +
  labs(title = "Annual Correlations Between Exported Goods and IPI", 
       x = "Year",
       y = "Correlation")

Year 2015 is apart, it is found that there is a positive correlation between exported goods and IPI. Especially after year 2016, all yearly correlations seem to exceed 0.75 indicating there is a strong relationship between exported goods and IPI

Conclusions and Remarks

In this study, the correlation between these metrics and some time series related properties are examined. In the time series part, we have seen a clear upward trend and an annual seasonal pattern in the all metrics without further analysis, which is also derived from autocorrelation graphs. In the correlation analysis part, we found a high correlation between the number of employed people and ipi and relatively high correlation between ipi and exported goods. There is no significant correlation seen between the number of employed people and exported goods.
